<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900604-0063</DOCNO><DOCID>900604-0063.</DOCID><HL>   SEC Charges Ex-Broker   Misspent Athletes' Funds</HL><DATE>06/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><IN>SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)</IN><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commission istrying to sack a former Robinson-Humphrey Co. broker forallegedly misappropriating more than $1 million from at least18 professional football players.   In a complaint filed in federal court in Atlanta, the SECcharged that broker Oscar Ayala of Marietta, Ga., defraudedthe players, who held accounts at the Shearson Lehman HuttonInc. unit from 1988 to the present. The SEC asks that he beenjoined from such activity and seeks unspecified relief.</LP><TEXT>   The agency alleges that Mr. Ayala, instead of purchasingsecurities for his clients, misappropriated at least $1million in funds for his personal use. A federal judge hasissued a temporary restraining order freezing Mr. Ayala'sbank and securities accounts and prohibiting the destructionof any records relating to the transactions.   The agency's Atlanta regional administrator, RichardWessel, said Robinson-Humphrey brought the matter to theattention of the SEC and other law enforcement agencies. Mr.Ayala's lawyer, Gary Freed, said that his client also isunder investigation by the Justice Department for possiblecriminal prosecution and that his client would be eager tohuddle with the SEC to settle the case. He added, &quot;We feelthat all of the accusations are not accurate and areexaggerated.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>